Europe needs to restart immigration
Brussels – Over 900 migrants attempting to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
At the same time, the rescue ships Open Arms and Ocean Viking have been searching for a safe harbor where passengers on board can disembark throughout the summer.
The refugee and migrant camps on the Greek island of Lesbos are overcrowded, and the conditions at other camps in Libya are roughly the same.
Turkey has torn up the 2016 agreement to prevent migrants from entering the EU.
Despite Europe's desire to help immigrants and respect international law, it doesn't want to be overcrowded.
The number of refugees and migrants pouring into the EU surged in 2015-16 – many fleeing the Syrian war – significantly affecting intra-EU trust.
The massive influx of immigrants eroded the government's confidence in external EU borders and asylum management, and highlighted the futility of cooperation with migrant source countries.
Therefore, immigrants became a political football, a populist darling.
Under the leadership of President von der Leyen, the new European Commission must regain control over the issue of immigration while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
To this end, the EU needs to re-establish policies in four aspects and mobilize member states to act in the interests of Europe.
Firstly, the EU must urgently ensure the safety of its external borders, which is a prerequisite for keeping the internal borders open.
Any country where people can move freely within, including the United States, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia, will not outsource control of external borders to a state or region.
Controlling the EU's external borders must be a collective task and a national task.
The European Border and Coast Guard Agency Frontex must be further strengthened and should be deployed with joint patrols by member states – including coastlines and airports.
Europe needs to restart Operation Sophia to combat illegal immigration in the Mediterranean.
Secondly, Europe needs to handle economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Merging them has brought the asylum system to the brink of collapse; handling them separately would allow migrants who are concerned about their lives to speak out while their rights are protected.
Solving Europe's true economic and social needs requires effective blue or green card policies for economic migrants and implementing a comprehensive immigration goal.
This cannot be put off until the next migration crisis to consider introducing these mechanisms.
To achieve this, the EU must break the taboo.
Firstly, the number of economic migrants entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a common interest issue.
Secondly, the policy must clearly identify which immigrants are welcome.
Thirdly, member states must answer which EU help is needed to achieve a smooth immigration process.
Finally, visa and work permits must be brought to the surface to facilitate illegal immigrants returning to their countries of origin.
True, according to the EU treaty, each member state needs to manage immigrants coming from outside the EU on their own.
However, if the government can reach an agreement on the overall EU immigration target, it will be a major step forward.
On the other hand, member states can specify the source countries and specific requirements for economic migrants they want, as well as the EU budget resources they need to accommodate them.
This way, immigration acceptance will become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has already established an active immigration policy, selecting immigrants based on indicators such as source country, skills, and age level.
Europe can do the same.
Thirdly, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
Firstly, the all-or-nothing requirement of obliging EU member states to accept asylum seekers must be scrapped.
This requirement has damaged the atmosphere within the EU, but if the border, asylum, and immigration systems are fully effective, it may still be feasible.
Furthermore, it cannot be expected that the EU's frontline member states will be able to solve the problem of irregular migrants crossing external borders on their own.
Refugee camps are already overcrowded, and migrants are subjected to mistreatment by authorities, or being pushed towards the north.
The responsibility of the first member state of arrival must be supplemented by the cohesion of the European Union.
The European Union must also provide experts and funding to regulate the behavior and management capabilities of national asylum institutions.
Only then will the decision of the member states be respected throughout the Schengen area, and the integrity of the border travel zone will be ensured.
After regulating the behavior and management capabilities of national asylum institutions, the asylum application handling process can also be shared among member states.
Fourth, the EU should build stronger win-win cooperation with source countries and transit countries.
These connections are crucial for the legitimate repatriation of migrants who are prohibited from entering the EU.
To ensure cooperation, the EU should mobilize all diplomatic tools, including development aid and investment funds, as well as programs in the fields of security, trade, energy, agriculture, fisheries, climate action, aviation, and health.
The EU's migration target, as well as skills cooperation to prepare for European jobs, can be provided to third countries that are eager to receive stable remittances.
At the same time, the EU must address the root causes of migration.
This includes the demographic explosion in Sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; the spread of infectious diseases; ethnic conflicts; and a lack of job opportunities.
The EU's assistance should focus on rebuilding stability and reducing risks through supporting security, community resilience and good governance.
This success will make investments safer, unlock private and domestic financial resources, thus achieving national economic growth, job creation, and providing alternatives to migration.
The new European Commission has the opportunity to move the EU away from a subconscious reaction to the migration crisis and towards a more consistent and sustainable policy, both within and outside the EU.
We cannot afford to miss this opportunity.
